I"„<p>Participants consistently make hand gestures when tasked with <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/spatial-reasoning-is-the-confluence-of-all-senses">memorizing</a> a spatial configuration. Suppressing gestures leads to poor performance. The concrete gestures often <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/isomorphic-representations-partially-preserve-structure">reflect the abstract representations</a> being manipulated. Surprisingly, blind people also gesture. Body movement might be useful for <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/pose-detection-enables-kinesthetic-sketchnoting">supporting abstract reasoning</a>.</p>
